The Imperative Blueprint
To replicate exactly what your YAML file just did using only kubectl one-liners, you use three main techniques:
1. Recreate the Entire Manifest via One-Line Creation
You can pass the image pull policy, correct shell execution parameters, and multi-line script logic straight through a single terminal execution block.
Bash




# Force remove the previous cronjob imperatively
kubectl delete cj infytel-customerdeployment --ignore-not-found

# Re-create it fully operational using imperative overrides
kubectl create cronjob infytel-customerdeployment \
  --image=nginx \
  --schedule="*/1 * * * *" \
  --dry-run=client -o yaml \
  -- /bin/sh -c "echo 'This application is running on Kubernetes'; date" \
  | sed '/image:/a \        imagePullPolicy: IfNotPresent' \
  | kubectl apply -f -
Why sed is used imperatively here: The native kubectl create cronjob subcommand does not feature a dedicated CLI flag to specify an explicit --image-pull-policy. Piping the output to sed injects imagePullPolicy: IfNotPresent directly into your container context on the fly before sending it to the Kubernetes API engine.
Deep-Dive Imperative Troubleshooting (Step-by-Step)
Now that it's running smoothly, here is how you track, examine, and test its life cycle purely using the CLI.
Step A: Monitor the Heartbeat
To check when it last successfully triggered and whether it's accumulating stale or completed pods without opening files:
Bash




kubectl get cj,jobs,pods
Your successful run proved that LAST SCHEDULE will no longer read <none>. It will actively refresh with the exact elapsed time since the last minute rolled over.
Step B: Force an Immediate Run (No Waiting)
If you want to manually run the underlying script logic immediately to test an update without modifying your schedule, use the --from creation pattern:
Bash




kubectl create job --from=cronjob/infytel-customerdeployment manual-run-verify
This imperatively instantiates a standalone Job object copying your exact parameters (nginx, IfNotPresent, your echo script) to confirm execution runs clean.
Step C: Extracting Logs and Cleaning Up
Once your pods report a Completed status, retrieve the stdout logs using labels rather than searching for individual dynamic pod hashes:
Bash




# View logs for all executions spawned by this specific CronJob resource
kubectl logs -l batch.kubernetes.io/job-name

# Imperatively clean up all successfully processed jobs left behind on your nodes
kubectl delete jobs --field-selector status.successful=1
Step D: Freezing the Automation Imperatively
If you need to stop the cron engine from firing every single minute while you update something else in your cluster, you can toggle its execution flag live:
Bash




# Pause the cron execution engine completely
kubectl patch cj infytel-customerdeployment -p '{"spec":{"suspend":true}}'

# Resume standard operations 
kubectl patch cj infytel-customerdeployment -p '{"spec":{"suspend":false}}'
